{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522939"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:50:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:50:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13859"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13859"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.7,0.11,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6476"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6476"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50509"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1880"},{"type":"tags","id":"2493"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12890"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44303"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive exertional dyspnoea and reduced exercise tolerance. She also reports occasional episodes of light-headedness and presyncope. Nine months ago, she was diagnosed with bilateral pulmonary emboli and was treated with rivaroxaban for six months. She completed the course of anticoagulation three months ago. Her medical history includes iron deficiency anaemia, and mild asthma, as well as a post-partum pulmonary embolism at age 27, which was treated with warfarin for three months. She does not take any regular medications apart from a salbutamol inhaler as needed and iron supplements. She is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 118/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals a prominent pulmonary component of the second heart sound. Respiratory examination is unremarkable. There is no peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary pulmonary arterial hypertension","Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension","Recurrent pulmonary embolism","Deconditioning","Iron deficiency anaemia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension (CTEPH)\u003C/strong\u003E. CTEPH is a potential long-term complication of pulmonary embolism, occurring in 2-4% of patients after an acute pulmonary embolism. It is characterised by organised thromboembolic material and vascular remodelling that obstructs the pulmonary arteries, leading to increased pulmonary vascular resistance and pulmonary hypertension. The cardinal symptom is progressive dyspnoea, typically developing 6-24 months after the acute pulmonary embolism. The prominent pulmonary component of the second heart sound on examination is suggestive of pulmonary hypertension. This patient\u0027s history of two pulmonary embolic events (post-partum and nine months ago) significantly increases her risk of developing CTEPH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary pulmonary arterial hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly with progressive dyspnoea and signs of right heart strain. However, given this patient\u0027s history of multiple pulmonary emboli, CTEPH is more likely than idiopathic pulmonary arterial hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erecurrent pulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E is possible given her history, but the progressive nature of her symptoms over several months is more suggestive of a chronic process like CTEPH rather than an acute recurrent pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeconditioning\u003C/strong\u003E can cause dyspnoea and reduced exercise tolerance, but it would not typically cause presyncope or be associated with signs of pulmonary hypertension on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Eiron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential contributor to her dyspnoea and pre-syncopal episodes, but it is unlikely to be the primary cause given the signs of pulmonary hypertension on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension (CTEPH) is a potential long-term complication of pulmonary embolism that causes persistent dyspnoea.","CTEPH is characterised by organised thromboembolic material and vascular remodelling that obstructs pulmonary arteries, leading to pulmonary hypertension.","Ventilation-perfusion (V/Q) scanning is the initial imaging modality of choice for diagnosing CTEPH."],"references":["Verbelen T, Godinas L, Maleux G, Coolen J, Claessen G, Belge C, et al. Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension: diagnosis, operability assessment and patient selection for pulmonary endarterectomy. Ann Cardiothorac Surg. 2022;11(2):82-97. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9012197/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50509"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13859"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50509"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T13:32:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T13:32:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6476"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65073"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji"